{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775863373311,"sessionID":"ses_2864bbb32ffe3jJEubZGUoaXIp","part":{"id":"prt_d79b490ee001V53pLb901w7JO3","messageID":"msg_d79b47a17001W6TvKYhYbxuL8m","sessionID":"ses_2864bbb32ffe3jJEubZGUoaXIp","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_tool-9728aba677c0410ab5d7fbb696484c02","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-5_20260410T163124Z/changes/AR-017/proposal.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-5_20260410T163124Z/changes/AR-017/proposal.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # AR-017 — PicoD JWT 中间件 Proposal\n2: \n3: ## Purpose\n4: \n5: Implement a dedicated JWT authentication middleware for PicoD that provides secure RS256 token validation, runtime public key management for key rotation, and request body size limiting. This middleware ensures that all PicoD API endpoints (except health check) require valid JWT tokens issued by the Router, protecting sandbox pods from unauthorized access.\n6: \n7: **Current State**: JWT authentication was initially implemented as part of AR-015 within `pkg/picod/auth.go`. The implementation provides basic RS256 validation, public key loading from environment, and a Gin middleware function. However, the component lacks dedicated documentation, clear separation of concerns, and explicit support for key rotation scenarios.\n8: \n9: **Target State**: Well-documented JWT middleware component with:\n10: - `AuthManager` struct with thread-safe public key storage (`sync.RWMutex`)\n11: - `LoadPublicKeyFromEnv()` — PEM parsing with PKIX format validation\n12: - `AuthMiddleware()` — Gin middleware for Bearer token extraction and RS256 validation\n13: - `SetPublicKey()` / `GetPublicKey()` — Runtime key rotation support\n14: - Request body size limiting via `http.MaxBytesReader` after successful validation\n15: - Explicit rejection of non-RSA signing methods (HS256 attack prevention)\n16: - Clear error responses for authentication failures\n17: \n18: ## Scope\n19: \n20: ### In Scope\n21: \n22: | Deliverable | Description |\n23: |-------------|-------------|\n24: | `pkg/picod/auth.go` (document) | Document existing AuthManager, public key loading, JWT middleware implementation |\n25: | `pkg/picod/auth.go` (test coverage) | Ensure comprehensive test coverage for key rotation, token validation edge cases |\n26: | `pkg/picod/server.go` (integration) | Document middleware registration in NewServer, route group protection |\n27: | Documentation | Clear specification of PEM format requirements, JWT claim expectations |\n28: \n29: ### Implementation Details\n30: \n31: #### AuthManager Structure\n32: \n33: ```go\n34: type AuthManager struct {\n35:     publicKey *rsa.PublicKey\n36:     mutex     sync.RWMutex\n37: }\n38: ```\n39: \n40: - Thread-safe storage using `sync.RWMutex` for concurrent access\n41: - Supports runtime key rotation via `SetPublicKey()`\n42: - Initialized with public key from environment at startup\n43: \n44: #### Public Key Loading\n45: \n46: ```go\n47: func LoadPublicKeyFromEnv() (*rsa.PublicKey, error)\n48: ```\n49: \n50: - Reads `PICOD_AUTH_PUBLIC_KEY` environment variable\n51: - PEM decode with `PUBLIC KEY` block type (PKIX format)\n52: - PKIX parsing via `x509.ParsePKIXPublicKey`\n53: - Rejects non-RSA public keys\n54: - Returns error on missing/invalid key (fatal at startup)\n55: \n56: #### JWT Middleware\n57: \n58: ```go\n59: func (a *AuthManager) AuthMiddleware() gin.HandlerFunc\n60: ```\n61: \n62: **Validation Steps**:\n63: 1. Extract `Authorization` header; reject if missing → 401 \"missing authorization header\"\n64: 2. Verify `Bearer <token>` format; reject malformed → 401 \"invalid token format\"\n65: 3. Parse token with RSA public key; reject non-RSA signing method → 401 \"invalid signing method\"\n66: 4. Validate claims: `WithExpirationRequired`, `WithIssuedAt`, `WithLeeway(time.Minute)`\n67: 5. Handle specific errors: expired → 401 \"token is expired\", invalid signature → 401 \"invalid signature\"\n68: 6. On valid token: apply `http.MaxBytesReader` with `MaxBodySize` = 32 MiB\n69: 7. Call `c.Next()` to proceed to handler\n70: \n71: #### Constants\n72: \n73: | Name | Value | Purpose |\n74: |------|-------|---------|\n75: | `PublicKeyEnvVar` | `\"PICOD_AUTH_PUBLIC_KEY\"` | Environment variable for PEM public key |\n76: | `MaxBodySize` | `32 << 20` (32 MiB) | Request body size limit after JWT validation |\n77: \n78: #### Key Rotation Support\n79: \n80: ```go\n81: func (a *AuthManager) SetPublicKey(key *rsa.PublicKey)\n82: func (a *AuthManager) GetPublicKey() *rsa.PublicKey\n83: ```\n84: \n85: - Enables Router to push new public keys during key rotation\n86: - Thread-safe with mutex protection\n87: - No service restart required for key updates\n88: \n89: ### Out of Scope\n90: \n91: - JWT token issuance (handled by Router)\n92: - Private key management\n93: - JWT refresh token handling\n94: - Token revocation/blacklist\n95: - Multi-issuer validation\n96: - Audience claim validation\n97: - Role-based access control within tokens\n98: - Rate limiting per token\n99: - Token introspection endpoints\n100: \n101: ## Impact Analysis\n102: \n103: ### Upstream Dependencies\n104: \n105: | Dependency | Version | Impact |\n106: |------------|---------|--------|\n107: | `github.com/gin-gonic/gin` | v1.10+ | Gin middleware pattern; `gin.HandlerFunc`, `gin.Context` |\n108: | `github.com/golang-jwt/jwt/v5` | v5.2+ | JWT parsing; RSA signing method validation, claim options |\n109: | `crypto/rsa` | Standard | RSA public key type |\n110: | `crypto/x509` | Standard | PKIX public key parsing |\n111: | `encoding/pem` | Standard | PEM block decoding |\n112: | `sync` | Standard | `sync.RWMutex` for thread-safe key storage |\n113: | `net/http` | Standard | `http.MaxBytesReader` for body limiting |\n114: \n115: ### Downstream Consumers\n116: \n117: | Consumer | Method Usage |\n118: |----------|--------------|\n119: | Router JWT Issuer | Generates RS256 tokens validated by PicoD; must use matching private key |\n120: | Workload Manager | Injects `PICOD_AUTH_PUBLIC_KEY` into sandbox pod environment; coordinates key rotation with Router |\n121: | PicoD Server | Registers AuthMiddleware on `/api` route group in `NewServer` |\n122: | Python SDK | Obtains JWT from Router; includes in Authorization header for all PicoD API calls |\n123: | Health Endpoint | Unauthenticated; bypasses AuthMiddleware via direct route registration |\n124: \n125: ### Breaking Change Considerations\n126: \n127: - **PEM Format**: PKIX (`PUBLIC KEY` block) required; PKCS#1 (`RSA PUBLIC KEY`) rejected\n128: - **RSA Only**: HS256 tokens rejected; Router must issue RS256\n129: - **Expiration Required**: Tokens without `exp` claim rejected\n130: - **IssuedAt Required**: Tokens without `iat` claim rejected\n131: - **Body Size Limit**: 32 MiB limit may reject large file uploads\n132: \n133: ### Compatibility Notes\n134: \n135: 1. **Bearer Prefix**: Authorization header must use `Bearer ` prefix exactly\n136: 2. **Signing Method**: Only RSA methods (RS256, RS384, RS512) accepted; symmetric methods rejected\n137: 3. **Leeway**: 1-minute leeway for clock skew tolerance\n138: 4. **Thread Safety**: Public key can be rotated without stopping PicoD service\n139: 5. **Startup Fatal**: Missing/invalid `PICOD_AUTH_PUBLIC_KEY` causes fatal startup error\n140: \n141: ## Alternatives Considered\n142: \n143: ### Alternative 1: Kubernetes TokenReview\n144: \n145: **Approach**: Validate Kubernetes ServiceAccount tokens via TokenReview API.\n146: \n147: | Aspect | Evaluation |\n148: |--------|------------|\n149: | Pros | Native Kubernetes auth; no separate key management |\n150: | Cons | Requires kubelet API access; not available inside sandbox pod; high latency |\n151: \n152: **Decision**: Rejected. PicoD runs inside sandbox without direct kubelet access. Router-mediated JWT is more suitable for session-based auth.\n153: \n154: ### Alternative 2: HMAC JWT (HS256)\n155: \n156: **Approach**: Use shared secret for JWT signing/validation.\n157: \n158: | Aspect | Evaluation |\n159: |--------|------------|\n160: | Pros | Simpler key management; no key pair generation |\n161: | Cons | Secret must be shared with all PicoD instances; rotation requires secret distribution; less secure for multi-tenant scenarios |\n162: \n163: **Decision**: Rejected. RS256 allows public key distribution to PicoD while Router retains private key. Better security isolation.\n164: \n165: ### Alternative 3: OAuth 2.0 / OIDC\n166: \n167: **Approach**: Use external OAuth provider with introspection.\n168: \n169: | Aspect | Evaluation |\n170: |--------|------------|\n171: | Pros | Standard protocol; external identity management; refresh tokens |\n172: | Cons | Requires external provider; introspection latency; not suitable for per-sandbox auth |\n173: \n174: **Decision**: Rejected. Per-sandbox auth requires Router-generated tokens tied to specific sessions. External OAuth not applicable.\n175: \n176: ### Alternative 4: Static API Key\n177: \n178: **Approach**: Pre-shared static API key for authentication.\n179: \n180: | Aspect | Evaluation |\n181: |--------|------------|\n182: | Pros | Simple implementation; no JWT complexity |\n183: | Cons | No expiration; no per-session differentiation; rotation requires service restart; key leak catastrophic |\n184: \n185: **Decision**: Rejected. JWT provides expiration, session-specific claims, and secure rotation without service restart.\n186: \n187: ### Alternative 5: mTLS (Mutual TLS)\n188: \n189: **Approach**: Require client certificates for authentication.\n190: \n191: | Aspect | Evaluation |\n192: |--------|------------|\n193: | Pros | Strong security; no JWT complexity |\n194: | Cons | Certificate management overhead; requires client cert in SDK; Router proxy complexity |\n195: \n196: **Decision**: Rejected. JWT is simpler for HTTP API auth and matches Router's token-based session management.\n197: \n198: ## Risks\n199: \n200: | Risk | Mitigation |\n201: |------|------------|\n202: | Missing public key at startup | `klog.Fatalf` with clear error; deployment checklist includes PEM injection |\n203: | Invalid PEM format | `LoadPublicKeyFromEnv` validates decode + PKIX parse; returns descriptive error |\n204: | HS256 algorithm substitution attack | Middleware type-assert `*jwt.SigningMethodRSA`; reject non-RSA |\n205: | Expired token acceptance | `WithExpirationRequired` enforced; `WithIssuedAt` prevents future tokens |\n206: | Clock skew rejection | `WithLeeway(time.Minute)` provides tolerance |\n207: | Key rotation race | `sync.RWMutex` protects publicKey read/write |\n208: | Large request DoS | `http.MaxBytesReader` applied after JWT validation |\n209: | Missing Authorization header | Middleware returns 401 before reaching handler |\n210: | Replay attacks | Token expiration enforced; short-lived tokens from Router |\n211: \n212: ## Implementation Checklist\n213: \n214: 1. **AuthManager Initialization**\n215:    - `NewAuthManager()` calls `LoadPublicKeyFromEnv()`\n216:    - Fatal on missing/invalid key\n217:    - Initialize mutex for thread safety\n218: \n219: 2. **Public Key Loading**\n220:    - Read `PICOD_AUTH_PUBLIC_KEY` environment variable\n221:    - Trim whitespace from PEM string\n222:    - PEM decode; validate `PUBLIC KEY` block type\n223:    - Parse PKIX public key\n224:    - Type-assert to `*rsa.PublicKey`\n225:    - Return error on any validation failure\n226: \n227: 3. **Middleware Implementation**\n228:    - Extract Authorization header\n229:    - Validate `Bearer ` prefix\n230:    - Strip prefix to get token string\n231:    - Read publicKey with RLock\n232:    - Parse JWT with RSA key\n233:    - Validate RSA signing method\n234:    - Apply claim validators (exp, iat, leeway)\n235:    - Handle specific error cases with appropriate responses\n236:    - Apply MaxBytesReader on success\n237:    - Call Next()\n238: \n239: 4. **Key Rotation Methods**\n240:    - `SetPublicKey`: Lock, update, Unlock\n241:    - `GetPublicKey`: RLock, read, RUnlock\n242: \n243: 5. **Server Integration**\n244:    - Create AuthManager in `NewServer`\n245:    - Apply middleware to `/api` route group\n246:    - Health endpoint outside protected group\n247: \n248: 6. **Tests**\n249:    - Missing authorization header\n250:    - Invalid token format (no Bearer prefix)\n251:    - Expired token\n252:    - Invalid signature\n253:    - HS256 token rejection\n254:    - Valid RS256 token acceptance\n255:    - Key rotation during active requests\n256:    - PEM format validation (PKIX vs PKCS#1)\n257:    - Environment variable missing\n258:    - Concurrent key access\n259: \n260: ## References\n261: \n262: - `changes/AR-015/proposal.md` — Original PicoD implementation context\n263: - `pkg/picod/auth.go` — Existing implementation\n264: - `pkg/picod/server.go` — Middleware registration\n265: - `pkg/router/jwt.go` — Router JWT issuance (key pair generation)\n266: - [github.com/golang-jwt/jwt](https://github.com/golang-jwt/jwt)\n267: - [JWT Best Practices](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc8725)\n268: - [RSA vs HMAC JWT](https://auth0.com/blog/json-web-token-signing-algorithms-overview/)\n\n(End of file - total 268 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# AR-017 — PicoD JWT 中间件 Proposal\n\n## Purpose\n\nImplement a dedicated JWT authentication middleware for PicoD that provides secure RS256 token validation, runtime public key management for key rotation, and request body size limiting. This middleware ensures that all PicoD API endpoints (except health check) require valid JWT tokens issued by the Router, protecting sandbox pods from unauthorized access.\n\n**Current State**: JWT authentication was initially implemented as part of AR-015 within `pkg/picod/auth.go`. The implementation provides basic RS256 validation, public key loading from environment, and a Gin middleware function. However, the component lacks dedicated documentation, clear separation of concerns, and explicit support for key rotation scenarios.\n\n**Target State**: Well-documented JWT middleware component with:\n- `AuthManager` struct with thread-safe public key storage (`sync.RWMutex`)\n- `LoadPublicKeyFromEnv()` — PEM parsing with PKIX format validation\n- `AuthMiddleware()` — Gin middleware for Bearer token extraction and RS256 validation\n- `SetPublicKey()` / `GetPublicKey()` — Runtime key rotation support\n- Request body size limiting via `http.MaxBytesReader` after successful validation\n- Explicit rejection of non-RSA signing methods (HS256 attack prevention)\n- Clear error responses for authentication failures\n\n## Scope\n\n### In Scope","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-5_20260410T163124Z/changes/AR-017/proposal.md","time":{"start":1775863373276,"end":1775863373308}}}}
